label.value: Appendix L-Cell Glucagon-Like Peptide-Producing Neuroendocrine Tumor

value.value: A neuroendocrine tumor arising from the wall of the appendix, producing glucagon-like peptides.  Morphologically, it is characterized by the presence of neoplastic cells forming tubular or trabecular patterns.

label.value: Colon Enterochromaffin Cell Serotonin-Producing Neuroendocrine Tumor

value.value: A well differentiated neuroendocrine tumor that arises from the colon and produces serotonin.

label.value: Colon L-Cell Glucagon-Like Peptide-Producing Neuroendocrine Tumor

value.value: A neuroendocrine tumor that arises from the colon and produces glucagon-like peptides.  Morphologically, it is characterized by the presence of neoplastic cells forming tubular or trabecular patterns.

A neuroendocrine tumor that arises from the gastrointestinal tract and produces glucagon-like peptides.  Morphologically, it is characterized by the presence of neoplastic cells forming tubular or trabecular patterns.

label.value: Small Intestinal Small Cell Neuroendocrine Carcinoma

value.value: An aggressive, high-grade, and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation that arises from the small intestine.  It is characterized by the presence of malignant small cells.

An allogenic whole tumor cell vaccine with potential antineoplastic activity.  B7 transfected melanoma cell vaccine consists of melanoma cells that have been induced to express the human leukocyte antigen (HLA) B7.  Vaccination with these altered cells may elicit an anti-tumor immune response via CD8+ cytotoxic T lymphocytes (CTL). (NCI04)

A gastrin-producing neuroendocrine tumor that arises from the small intestine.  It is characterized by the presence of uniform cells that form pseudorosettes.  The neoplastic cells have uniform nuclei and small amount of eosinophilic cytoplasm.

label.value: Small Intestinal Enterochromaffin Cell Serotonin-Producing Neuroendocrine Tumor

value.value: A well differentiated neuroendocrine tumor that arises from the small intestine and produces serotonin.

label.value: Small Intestinal L-Cell Glucagon-Like Peptide-Producing Neuroendocrine Tumor

value.value: A neuroendocrine tumor that arises from the small intestine and produces glucagon-like peptides.  Morphologically, it is characterized by the presence of neoplastic cells forming tubular or trabecular patterns.
A somatostatin-producing neuroendocrine tumor that arises from the small intestine.

A usually malignant pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor producing vasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP).  It may or may not be associated with inappropriate secretion of VIP and an associated clinical syndrome.
A neuroendocrine tumor that arises from the small intestine and produces vasoactive intestinal peptide.

A usually polypoid neoplasm that arises from the glandular epithelium of the colonic and rectal mucosa. It is characterized by a tubular architectural pattern. The neoplastic glandular cells have dysplastic features.
An adenoma that arises from the colon or rectum.  It is characterized by the presence of moderate epithelial dysplasia.
An adenoma that arises from the colon or rectum.  It is characterized by the presence of mild epithelial dysplasia.
A precancerous neoplastic process that affects the colon or rectum.  It is characterized by low or high grade dysplasia of the mucosal epithelium.  There is no evidence of invasion.
A synthetic vaccine combining the peptide antigens of two proteins, ras oncoprotein and tumor suppressor p53. (NCI04)

A precancerous neoplastic process that affects the colon or rectum.  It is characterized by mild epithelial dysplasia and mild architectural alterations of the mucosal epithelium.  There is no evidence of invasion.

A precancerous neoplastic process that affects the colon or rectum.  It is characterized by moderate or severe epithelial dysplasia and complex architectural alterations of the mucosal epithelium.  There is no evidence of invasion.
A precancerous neoplastic process that affects the small intestine.  It is characterized by low or high grade dysplasia of the mucosal epithelium.  There is no evidence of invasion.

label.value: Small Intestinal Low Grade Intraepithelial Neoplasia

value.value: A precancerous neoplastic process that affects the small intestine.  It is characterized by mild epithelial dysplasia and mild architectural alterations of the mucosal epithelium.  There is no evidence of invasion.

label.value: Small Intestinal High Grade Intraepithelial Neoplasia

value.value: A precancerous neoplastic process that affects the small intestine.  It is characterized by moderate or severe epithelial dysplasia and complex architectural alterations of the mucosal epithelium.  There is no evidence of invasion.
A rare Burkitt lymphoma that arises from the colon.

An ectopic ACTH producing pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor. It may be associated with Cushing syndrome. Most patients present with metastases at the time of diagnosis and the prognosis is usually poor.

label.value: Stage 0 Lung Cancer AJCC v6 and v7

value.value: Stage 0 includes: Tis, N0, M0.  Tis: Carcinoma in situ.  N0: No regional lymph node metastasis.  M0: No distant metastasis. (AJCC 6th and 7th eds.)

A plasma cell disorder in which an abnormal amount of a single immunoglobulin is present in the serum. Paraproteinemias may be seen in conjunction with various carcinomas, chronic inflammatory and infectious conditions, and other diseases. --2004
Carcinoma that is spread throughout the body.

A immunoconjugate comprised of a monoclonal antibody directed against the pancarcinoma antigen TAG-72.conjugated to PA-DOTA, a bifunctional chelant.  TAG-72 is a protein/sugar complex found on the surface of many cancer cells, including breast, colon, and pancreatic cancer cells. (NCI04)
Cancer that is spread throughout the body, a metastatic phenomenon.

label.value: Peripheral Primitive Neuroectodermal Tumor of Soft Tissues

value.value: A small round cell tumor with neural differentiation arising from the soft tissues.

An epithelioid sarcoma predominantly involving the pelvis, perineum, and genital organs.  It tends to have a more aggressive clinical course as compared to the more frequently seen distal-type epithelioid sarcoma.

An epithelioid sarcoma involving the extremities.  It usually presents as nodular masses in the dermis and subcutaneous tissues or in the tendons and fascia.  It frequently recurs and metastasizes to other anatomic sites.  The most common sites of metastasis are the lungs, lymph nodes, bones, and brain.
An infiltrating carcinoma of the bladder that has not invaded into the bladder muscularis propria.
A benign neoplasm which is composed of adipocytes and arises from the surface of the bone or the medullary cavity.
A very rare schwannoma of the bone. It is often located in the mandible and is well circumscribed.

label.value: Benign Osteoclastic Giant Cell-Rich Tumor of Bone

value.value: A giant cell tumor that arises from the bone and is characterized by the absence of local aggression and lack of metastatic potential.
A benign neoplasm arising from the fibrous soft tissues of the gingiva. It is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped fibroblasts and numerous dilated vascular channels.

A morphologic variant of fibroma with numerous dilated vascular channels that arises from the posterolateral wall of the roof of the nasal cavity or lateral nasopharynx. It is associated with somatic mutations in CTNNB1 gene in the majority of cases.

A recombinant, chimeric protein derived from a melanoma antigenic epitope (MAGE-3) and recognized by specific cytotoxic T lymphocytes.  MAGE-3, a human peptide epitope present in the cytosol of melanoma cells, may be expressed as the fusion protein D1/3-Mage-3; this fusion protein may boost antitumoral immune responses when used in a vaccine formulation. (NCI04)
A morphologic variant of fetal rhabdomyoma characterized by the presence of a prominent myxoid stroma and primitive skeletal spindle cells.
A rare malignant tumor of soft tissue characterized by a bimorphic pattern composed of undifferentiated small round cells and islands of well differentiated hyaline cartilage.
A chondrosarcoma that arises either in a pre-existing enchondroma or within the cartilaginous cap of a pre-existing osteochondroma.

A lipoma usually occurring in the extremities of young children (usually boys). It is characterized by lobules of adipose tissue, separated by fibrous septa.  The adipose tissue is composed of mature adipocytes and lipoblasts. The lipoblasts may be scarce, depending on the age of the patient.
An angiomyolipoma arising from the liver.

A neoplastic process characterized by a diffuse poorly circumscribed overgrowth of adipose tissue in the pelvic region.  Clinical presentation includes complaints of back and abdominal pain, urinary frequency, perineal pain and constipation.  It predominately affects black males.

A neoplastic process characterized by a diffuse poorly circumscribed overgrowth of adipose tissue in the face, upper middle back, and sternal region. It is associated with adrenocortical steroid therapy or an increase in endogenous adrenocortical hormone.
A neoplastic process characterized by a diffuse poorly circumscribed overgrowth of adipose tissue in the mediastinum.

A benign adipocytic neoplasm, characterized by ill-defined tumor margins and the presence of variable proportions of mild to moderately atypical spindle cells, adipocytes, lipoblasts, pleomorphic cells, multinucleated giant cells, and a myxoid or collagenous extracellular matrix. It has a low tendency for local recurrence if incompletely excised. Unlike conventional atypical lipomatous tumors, there is no risk for dedifferentiation. (WHO 2020)

One allele of the transforming chimeric gene resulting from a t(11;22) translocation that is found frequently in patients with Ewing's sarcoma or primitive neuroectodermal tumors (PNET). EWS-FLI 1 type 1 encodes a protein, mTOR, that is a central regulator of translation and cell proliferation. mTOR activates the mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK) signaling pathway, resulting in neoplastic transformation. Antisense oligonucleotides that target EWS-FLI 1 type 1 have been used investigationally to treat this genetic anomaly, resulting in cell cycle arrest at G1 phase.  (NCI04)
